<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,334,824]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,373,399]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[412,515,373,399]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">holotype</typeStatus>
is a small colony, 
<quantity box="[739,798,373,399]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
in height and 
<quantity box="[971,1030,373,399]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
in width. Branching is irregularly dichotomous (
<figureCitation box="[322,392,412,438]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,255,1967,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,879,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,879,1943]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. Eugorgia alba, holotype: A, colony; B, detail of branches; C, coenenchymal sclerites." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/188711/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[378,392,412,438]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Two main branches arise from a short stem, 
<quantity box="[973,1055,412,438]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="cm" value="1.2">1.2 cm</quantity>
long, and subdivide up to three times. The holdfast is missing from the 
<typeStatus box="[622,728,450,476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">holotype</typeStatus>
, but from Bielschowsky’s illustration (
<number box="[1186,1250,450,476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1929.0">1929</number>
: plate 
<number box="[1327,1343,450,476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
, fig. 
<number box="[1399,1428,450,476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="15.0">15</number>
) it seems incrusting. Branches are slightly compressed in cross section, 
<quantity box="[1026,1097,489,515]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
in diameter at the base and tapered, more rounded at the branchlets. Branchlets are up to 
<quantity box="[870,938,528,554]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Unbranched final twigs reach up to 
<quantity box="[217,275,566,592]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
with pointed tips, about 
<quantity box="[565,633,566,592]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Polyps retract within slightly raised polyp-mounds with oval apertures (
<figureCitation box="[331,401,605,631]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,255,1967,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,879,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,879,1943]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. Eugorgia alba, holotype: A, colony; B, detail of branches; C, coenenchymal sclerites." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/188711/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[386,401,605,631]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Polyp-mounds are distributed in 
<number box="[828,873,605,631]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
longitudinal rows on the branches, and sparsely placed. Colour of the colony is white. Sclerites of the coenenchyme are mostly colourless, some with a pale pink hue. They are mostly double discs reaching up to 
<quantity box="[787,906,682,708]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.075">0.075 mm</quantity>
in length, and 
<quantity box="[1079,1183,682,708]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.06">0.06 mm</quantity>
in width (
<figureCitation box="[1301,1370,682,708]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,255,1967,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,879,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,879,1943]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. Eugorgia alba, holotype: A, colony; B, detail of branches; C, coenenchymal sclerites." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/188711/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[1356,1370,682,708]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C, 
<number box="[1404,1422,682,708]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="4.0">4</number>
). Spindles reach up to 
<quantity box="[394,498,721,747]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
in length, and 
<quantity box="[670,774,721,747]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
in width, with 
<number box="[949,993,721,747]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6</number>
whorls of tubercles, with ends mostly acute. No anthocodial rods were found in the samples.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
